ON MONDAY, JUNE 1, 1992 A TANK TRUCK OWNED AND OPERATED BY NORTHEASTENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES, INC. (NES) DEPARTED OUR FACILITY ON ROUTE TO MEDUSSACEMENT IN WAMPUM, PA. THE TRUCK LEFT OUR FACILITY AT APPROXIMATELY 6:30AMDRIVEN BY RONALD P. EDICK AND WAS CARRYING A MIXTURE OF PAINT AND PAINTTHINNERS USED AT CEMENT KILNS AS AN ALTERNATE FUEL TO OIL IN HEATING TEIR KILN.THE DRIVER HAD PERFORMED HIS ROUTINE PRE-SHIPMENT CHECK WITH THE EXCEPTION OFCOMPLETELY SECURING THE DOME LID ON TOP OF THE TANKER. AS THE TRUCK TURNED THECORNER OF PETERBORO ST. AND CANAL ROAD, CANSTOTA, THERE WAS EVIDENTLY ENOUGHMOVEMENT OF LIQUID INSIDE THE TANKER TO CAUSE SOME OF THE MATERIAL TO LEAK OUTTHE TOP HATCH, AND SPILL ONTO THE ROADWAY INFRONT OF KEY BANK. THE DRIVER WASALERTED TO THE PROBLEM BY A TRUCK DRIVER BEHIND HIM WHO FOLLOWED HIM TO CLARK'SPETROLEUM (APPROXIMATELY 1 MILE FROM THE SCENE OF THE INCIDENT) TO INFORM HIMOF THE INCIDENT. ONCE RON EDICK WAS SO INFORMED, HE CLIMBED UP ON TOP OF THETANK,SECURELY FASTENED THE DOME LID, WIPED UP THE RESIDUE AROUND THE LID ANDBORUGH THE RUCK BACK TO THE FACILITY AND ALERTED THE FACILITY TO THE SPILL. ACREW WAS DISPATCHED TO THE SCENE TO INITIATE CLEAN UP EFFORTS. THE LOCALCANASTOTA POLICE AND FIRE DEPARTMENTS WER NOTIFIED AS WELL AS THE AGENCIESLISTED ABOVE. LIQUID VOLUMES IN TANKERS ARE CALCULATED BY "STICKING" THE TANK,MEASURING THE NUMBER OF INCHES OF LIQUID, THEN REFERRING TO A CALIBRATION CHART TO CONVERT TO GALLONS. BY COMPARING THE LEVELS BEFORE ANDAFER, NES STAFF CALCULATED AN ORIGINAL LOSS OF 26 GALLONS OF PRODUCT. NESPERONNEL INVESTIGATED THE ROADWAY BETWEEN KEY BANK AND CLARK'S PETROLEUM TO SEEIF ADDITIONAL WASTE HAD BEEN RELEASED. NEITHER NES NOR THE CANASTOTA POLICEWERE ABLE TO FIND ANY SIGNS OF ADDITIONAL RELEASES. FAULT LIES WITH BOTH THE SHIPPER (NES) AND THE DRIVER FOR FAILING TO COMPLETELY CHECK OVER THE VEHICLE PRIOR TO LEAVING.  INTERNAL DISCIPLINARY MEASURES WERE TAKEN AS WELL AS IN-HOUSE INFORMATIONAL/REVIEW PROCEDURES MEETING TO EMPHASIZE PROPER PROCEDURES INVOLVING PREPARATION OF HAZARDOUS MATERIALS FOR SHIPMENT

THE UNLOADER AT THE CONSIGNEE OPENED VALVES AND TOOK A SAMPLE OF THE PRODUCT FOR THE LAB.  OUR DRIVER ATTACHED THE HOSE TO THE VALVE AND WAS STANDING BY THE TRAILER WAITING FOR THE UNLOADER TO RETURN.  AFTER ABOUT 10 MINS. DRIVER NOTICED PRODUCT START TO COME OUT OF THE END OF THE HOSE. HE PICKED UP THE END OF THE HOSE AND TIGHTENED THE VALVE.  ABOUT 3 TO 4 GALS HAD RUN OUT OF THE HOSE. column168: ON WEDNESDAY, JUNE 24, 1992 AT 5:30 AM APPROXIMATELY 45 GALLONS OF WASTE FUEL CONTAINING OILS, ALCOHOL AND KETONES SPILLED FROM THE REAR DOME OF A RESOURCE TRANSPORTATION SERVICES (RTS) TANK TRAILER.  THE DRIVER NOTICED THE LEAK AS HE WAS PULLING OUT ONTO THE ROAD IN FRONT OF HIS FACILITY.  HE STOPPED THE LEAK BY TIGHTENING DOWN THE DOME LID AND PARKED THE TANK TRAILER. THE SPILL WAS CONTAINED ON A 3 TO 4 HUNDRED-FOOT STRETCH OF THE SOUTHBOUND LANE OF BATTLEGROUND RD.  THE GNI GROUP INC'S EMERGENCY RESPONSE TEAM APPLIED ABSORBENT TO IMMOBILIZE THE SPILL, CLOSED THE SOUTHBOUND LANE AT THE SPILL AREA AND BEGAN DIRECTING TRAFFIC AROUND THE AFFECTED AREA.  IN ADDITION, A LOCAL CLEAN UP CONTRACTOR, EMTECH, WAS HIRED TO WASH THE AFFECTED ROAD AREA USING A HOT WATER PRESSURE WASHER,  THE WASH WATER WAS COLLECTED FOR DEEPWELL INJECTION AT DISPOSAL SYSTEMS, INC.  THE CONTAMINATED ABSORBENT WAS PLACED INTO CONTAINERS FOR DISPOSAL IN THE SOLIDIFICATION PROCESS AT DISPOSAL SYSTEMS FOR EVENTUAL INCINERATION AT CHEMICAL WASTE MANAGEMENT (PORT ARTHUR INCINERATOR). THE SPILL WAS COMPLETELY CLEANED UP BY 2:30 PM.  NO TEXAS WATERS WERE AFFECTED AND NO ENVIRONMENTAL THREATS WERE POSED BY THIS SPILL.  IN ADDITION, NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES OCCURRED DUE TO THE SPILL.

ON 6-10-92, PRODUCT LEAKING FROM A FIBER DRUM CAUSED BY PUNCTURE OF FORKLIFT ON OUR DOCK.  DOCK SUPERVISOR CONTROLLED THE SPILLAGE BY SOAKING IT UP WITH AN OIL DRY ABSORBANT, AND PLACING ABSORBANT IN SALVAGE DRUM. ON 6-11-92 A.M. SERVICE MASTER WAS CONTACTED FOR ASSISTANCE.  THEY REFERRED US TO INFOTRAC WHO SUGGESTED THAT WE CONTACT AN AGENCY WHICH SPECIALIZED IN DISPOSAL OF HAZARDOUS WASTE.  WE CONTACTED PDC LABORATORIES IN PEORIA, IL WHICH, AFTER TESTING A SAMPLE OF THIS ABSORBANT, TOLD US IT IS A NON-CORROSIVE WASTE AND CAN BE DISPOSED IN OUR DUMPSTER.

column168: AT THE TOP REAR OF TANKER TRAILER, THERE IS A (3") THREE INCH MALE HOSE FITTING WITH CAMLOCK CLOSURE.  AT SOMETIME DURING TRANSPORT BETWEEN ORIGIN AND DESTINATION THIS CAP CAME OFF. THE MATERIAL WAS BLOTTED WITH SAND SWEPT UP.  THE LARGEST EXPENSSE IS FOR THE REMOVAL OF ASPHALT FROM VEHICLES THAT DROVE THRU AT TIME OF SPILL.  THE CAMLOCK CLOSURE HAD BEEN REPLACED AND CHAINED BETWEEN CAMLOCK EARS SO IT CANNOT COME OFF IN TRANSPORT.

column168: DRIVER WAS LOADED AT HRI FACILITY ON 6-12-92.  UPON DEPARTURE OF FACILITY THE DRIVER FAILED TO INSPECT VENT SCRUBBER HOSE TO INSURE IT WAS IN PROPER POSITION FOR TRANSPORTATION.  UPON LEAVING THE FACILITY A SERIES OF THREE MINOR SPILLS OCCURRED.  THE FIRST SPILL OCCURRED ON PROFIT DRIVE. APPROXIMATELY 1 GALLON SPILLED AT THIS LOCATION.  THE SECOND SPILL OCCURRED ON DIVIDEND & CORPORATION INTERSECTION.  APPROXIMATELY 2 GALLONS SPILLED AT THIS LOCATION.  THE THIRD AND FINAL SPILL OCCURRED AT THE W.W. WHITE & I-10 INTERSECTION.  APPROXIMATELY 5 GALLONS SPILLED AT THIS LOCATION.  A CREW OF USPCI EMPLOYEES EMPLOYED AT THE HRI FACILITY IMMEDIATELY REMEDIATED THE SPILLED MATERIAL.  LOCAL AUTHORITIES WERE NOTIFIED INCLUDING THE TEXAS WATER COMMISSION AND NRC.

#1 HOOKED HOSE TO CUSTOMER'S TANK.  OPENED VALVES.  STATIONERY HOSE BURST. #1 CLOSED VALVES.  #1 BREATHED IN VAPORS.  WAS TAKEN TO HOSPITAL, TREATED AND RELEASED.  VAPORS TRAVELED TO NEARBY TRAILER WHERE TWO TEENAGE GIRLS LIVED.  THEY WENT TO THE DOCTOR, WERE TREATED AND RELEASED.  FIRE DEPARTMENT WASHED DOWN.
#1 DISCOVERED TRAILER LEAKING AT STAINLESS SECTION SEAM, 1 DROP EVERY SEVEN SECONDS.  LOAD WAS TRANSFERRED TO ANOTHER TRAILER.  TANK SENT FOR REPAIRS.

column168: TRAILER WAS LOADED IN ST. HELENS, OR AT 1:30 PM WITH 5350 GALLONS OF AQUA AMMONIA.  (97% OF TANK CAPACITY).  WHILE ENROUTE THE DRIVER STOPPED IN THE WEIGH STATION/REST AREA IN FEDERAL WAY, WA.  THE UNIT WAS PARKED ON AN INCLINE WITH THE REAR OF THE TRAILER DOWNHILL.  45 MINUTES LATER THE DRIVER WAS TOLD BY SCALE PERSONNEL THAT THE TRAILER WAS LEAKING. LEAK WAS COMING FROM THE CLEANOUT CAR AT THE REAR OF THE UNIT, WITHIN THE CATCH BASIN AROUND THE DOME AREA.  PRODUCT WAS LEAKING INTO THE CATCH BASIN AND RUNNING DOWN THE OVERFLOW TUBE AND DRIPPING ON THE GROUND AT A RATE OF 1-2 DROPS PER SECOND.  STATE POLICE OFFICERS AT THE SCALE WOULD NOT ALLOW HIM TO REPOSITION THE UNIT AT THIS TIME. ONE HOUR LATER WHEN A SGT. ARRIVED ON SCENE AND OUR SPILL RESPONSE CONTRACTOR ARRIVED, THE DRIVER WAS ALLOWED TO REPOSITION THE UNIT AND THE LEAKING STOPPED.  GASKET & CLEAN OUT CAP WERE REPLACED, SMALL SPILL AREA UNDER TRAILER WAS CLEANED UP.  UNIT WAS RETURNED TO SERVICE AND CONTINUED ON TO IT'S DESTINATION.  SPILL WAS DUE TO DEFECTIVE GASKET.  PARKING ON A SLOPE AND POSSIBLY THE SUN ON THE TANK CREATING PRESSURE CONTRIBUTED TO THE PROBLEM.  DRIVERS REMINDED TO CHECK CLEANOUT CAP GASKETS AS PART OF NORMAL WORK ROUTINE AND THIS INCIDENT WILL BE REVIEWED AT NEXT SCHEDULED DRIVER TRAINING SESSION.

UPON ARRIVAL AT ELTEX CHEMICAL, TWO DRUMS WERE DISCOVERED TO HAVE LOOSE BUNG SEALS AND PRODUCT FROM THESE DRUMS SPILLED ONTO THE TRAILER FLOOR IN THE UNLOADING PROCESS.  ONCE ALL DRUMS WERE UNLOADED, THE AREA OF THE TRAILER FLOOR AFFECTED WAS COVERED WITH FLOOR DRY AND THEN SWEPT THOROUGHLY.  ALL DRUMS AND RESIDUE WERE ACCEPTED BY ELTEX CHEMICAL.

A 55 GALLON DRUM OF SODIUM HYDROXIDE SOLUTION WAS FOUND LEAKING IN TRAILER #15-1280 AT THE BISMARCK, ND TERMINAL.  LACK OF DUNNAGE ON THE TRAILER FLOOR CAUSED AN ABRASION ON THE BOTTOM OF THE DRUM.  THE LEAKING DRUM AND ALL OF THE SPILLED PRODUCT WERE REMOVED FROM THE TRAILER PER EMERGENCY RESPONSE GUIDELINES AND RETURNED TO THE SHIPPER IN A DOT SALVAGE DRUM. THE TRAILER WAS CLEANED AT THE BISMARCK TERMINAL. SHIPMENTS OF DRUMS WILL BE LOADED ON TOP OF CARDBOARD DUNNAGE TO PREVENT FUTURE INCIDENTS OF THIS NATURE.

SHIPPER DID NOT CONFORM TO LOCAL, STATE, OR FEDERAL REGULATIONS FOR A SHIPMENT OF THIS NATURE.  SHIPPER DID NOT USE AN APPROVED D.O.T. BOX. THERE WAS NO INTERNAL TOP OR BOTTOM COVER AS REQUIRED .  THE APPROVED AMOUNT WHICH CAN BE SHIPPED IS ONE QUART.  THE AMOUNT SHIPPED WAS EXCEEDED 20 TIMES, IE, 5 GALLONS WERE SHIPPED IN EACH PLASTIC PAIL.  DAMAGE PORTIONS ARE AWAITING DISPOSAL THROUGH UPS' HAZARDOUS MATERIAL SERVICE, WHICH IS MALLINCKRODT.
PACKAGE HAD LOOSE CAP.  DISPOSED OF FOLLOWING HAZARDOUS MATERIAL PROCEDURE.  CUSTOMER SERVICE SHOULD FOLLOW UP WITH SHIPPER.  DIAMOND LABLE NOT AFFIXED TO PACKAGES.

MANUFACTURER CONTACTED AND ADVISED CLEANUP WITH WATER OKAY. TANK CAR WAS REPORTED LEAKING IN ROCKY MOUNT, NC.  I CONTACTED TRAINMASTER WHO REPORTED A SMALL CLOUD HOOVERING ABOVE DOME.  I CONTACTED SHIPPER THROUGH CHEMTREC.  ALSO SET BOE INSPECTOR TO INSPECT CAR. INSPECTOR FOUND SMALL LEAK AROUND LIQUID VALVE.  AT FIRST THE LEAK WOULD NOT STOP THAT AFTERNONN.  SHIPPER AND INSPECTOR LOOKED AT CAR AGAINS AND FOUND IT NOT LEAKING.  GARY BRAMOCK OF CSX HAZMAT INSPECTED CAR FOLLOWING DAY.  HE HAD CAR MOVED AND SHOOK.  AFTER HE FOUND NO LEAK.  CAR WAS MOVED ONTO DESTINATION.
CAR WAS DISCOVERED LEAKING IN YARD.  CAR WAS ISOLATED AND SHIPPER CONTACTED FOR REPAIR.  RESCAR REPLACED BLOWN RUPTURE DISC.  CAR WAS RELEASED AT 23:00, 6/30.

TRUCK OPERATOR WAS MAKING A PUMP OFF DELIVERY AT CUSTOMERS LOCATION, WHEN THE DELIVERY HOSE CAME OFF THE TRUCK PUMP.  APPROX 400 GALS. OF FUEL OIL WAS SPILLED ON A GRAVEL AND DIRT DRIVEWAY.  CUSTOMER HAD THE EQUIPMENT AND MATERIAL ON HAND AT THE TIME TO IMMEDIATELY DIKE AND COVER THE AREA WITH ABSORBENT CRUSHED STONE.  WITHIN 4 HOURS OF THE SPILL THE CONTAMINATED SOIL WAS BEING REMOVED AND PUT ON PLASTIC AND COVERED.  THE TRUCK OPERATOR WAS IN THE CAB OF THE TRUCK AT THE TIME OF THE SPILL.  HE WAS ADVISED BY THE CUSTOMERS MECHANIC THAT THE HOSE COME OFF AND PRODUCT WAS RUNNING OUT FROM UNDER THE TRUCK.  THE TRUCK OPERATOR WAS TERMINATED ON 6/29/92 FOR FAILURE TO FOLLOW INSTRUCTIONS.

HEAVY SKID LOADED ON TOP OF PAILS - NO CUSHION MATERIAL USED BETWEEN FREIGHT.  OVER THE CAUSE OF TRAVEL THE WEIGHT CRUSHED THE PLASTIC PAILS CAUSING THE LIQUID TO SPILL OUT OF 2 PAILS.  SECURED CLIP AREA, IDENTIFIED THE HAZARD.  CONTACTED CHEMTREC FOR HANDLING, NOTIFIED LEONARD LEACH, CONTACTED CONSIGNEE FOR DISPOSITION (THEY ACCEPTED FRT).  NOTIFED ORIGIN TERMINAL OF IMPROPER LOADING.  SENT FOUR PHOTOS.

column62: Improper Preparation for Transportation; Water Damage
column168: A CUBIC YARD DOT-E 9920 FIBER BOX WAS LOADED WITH WHAT WAS OBSERVED TO BE A DRY CHROMIUM LUDGE WASTE.  EN ROUTE, RESIDUAL LIQUID THAT WAS NOT VISIBLE AT THE TIME THE CONTAINER WAS LOADED, SEPARATED FROM THE MATERIAL CAUSING THE FIBER BOX TO SPLIT OPEN ALONG THE BOTTOM SEAM.  THE MAJORITY OF THE MATERIAL THAT WAS RELEASE WAS CONTAINED IN THE VAN TRAILER. APPROXIMATELY ONE QUART OF THE MATERIAL, HOWEVER, DID ESCAPE ONTO THE PAVEMENT OF THE TRUCK STOP.  THE DRIVER OF THE VEHICLE IDENTIFIED THIS SITUATION WHILE CONDUCTING A ROUTINE LOAD CHECK AND IMMEDIATELY PLACED POLY SHEETING UNDER THE LEAKING PORTION OF THE TRAILER EFFECTIVELY CONTAINING THE RELEASE.  THE DRIVER THEN NOTIFIED  HIS IMMEDIATE SUPERVISOR WHO INTURN CONTACTED THE PENNSYLVANIA DEPARTMENT OF ENVIRONMENTAL RESOURCES.  THE STATE OF PENNSYLVANIA NOTIFIED THE LOCAL AUTHORITIES TO INFORM THEM OF THE SITUATION AND DISPATCHED ONE OF THEIR INVESTIGATORS WHO MONITORED THE CLEAN-UP OPERATION.  AT THIS TIME, CLEAN HARBORS OF KINGSTON, INC. DISPATCHED A FIELD SERVICE CREW FROM THE DEPTFORD NJ AREA.  UPON ARRIVAL, THE FIELD CREW RECONTAINERIZED THE MATERIAL FORM THE LEAKING CUBIC YARD BOX INTO 55 GALLON DRUMS AND THEN PROCEEDED TO CLEAN-UP THE MATERIAL THAT HAD ESCAPED FROM THE TRAILER.  THE INSIDE OF THE TRAILER WAS DECONTAMINATED AND ALL DEBRIS RESULTING FROM THE RELEASE WAS CONTAINERIZED AND THE MATERIAL WAS SHIPPED TO A FULLY LICENSED WASTE MANAGEMENT FACILITY FOR DISPOSAL.  IN ORDER TO PREVENT THE RECURRENCE OF THIS SITUATION, ALL PERSONNEL RESPONSIBLE FOR LOADING THIS TYPE OF CONTAINER WILLBE REQUIRED TO INSPECT THE LOAD FOR ANY EVIDENCE OF RESIDUAL LIQUID.  IN THE EVENT THAT RESIDUAL LIQUID IS FOUND OR SUSPECTED, THE MATERIAL IS TO BE RECONTAINERIZED INTO APPROVED CONTAINERS PRIOR TO TRANSPORTATION.

column58: Closure (e.g., Cap, Top, or Plug); Piping or Fittings
column168: A ROLL-OFF CONTAINER CONTAINING 1,1,1-TRICHLOROETHANE CONTAMINATED SOIL WAS WN ROUTE TO TRADE WASTE INCINERATION, LOCATED IN SAUGET IL FROM CLEAN HARBORS OC BRAINTREE, INC.  LOCATED AT 385 QUINCY AAVENUE BRAINTREE, MA 02184 ON JUNE 16, 1992.  UPON EXIT FROM CLEAN HARBORS OF BRAINTREE, INC. THE LOAD WAS CHECKED AND NO FREE LIQUIDS WERE PRESENT.  DURING THE COURSE OF THE TRIP, THE DRIVER CONDUCTED A LOAD CHECK AND TIRE CHECK AND NOTICED A SMALL DRIP COMING FROM THE REAR PORTION OF THE ROLL-OFF CONTAINER.  HE IMMEDIATELY PLACE ABSORBENT MATERIAL UNDER THE PORTION OF THE VEHICLE WHERE THE LEAK WASNOTED A CALLED HIS IMMEDIATE SUPERVISOR WHO, IN TURN, NOTIFIED THE STATE OFPENNSYLVANIA.  THE STATE OF PENNSYLVANIA THEN NOTIFIED THEIR REGIONAL OFFICE COVERING ERIE COUNTY AND THE LOCAL AUTHORITIES.  A FIELD SERVICE CREW WAS IMMEDIATELY DISPATCHED FROM TEH CLEAN HARBOR PITTSBURG, PA SERVICE CENTER.  UPON ARRIVAL, THE CREW, ALONG WITH THE DRIVER, ADDED ABSORBENT MATERIAL TO THE LOAD EFFECTIVELY ABSORBING THE RESIDUAL LIQUID THAT HAD SEPARATED FROM THE SOLIDS DURING TRANSIT.  THE ABSORBENT MATERIAL THAT WAS INITIALLY USED TO COLLECT ANY MATERIAL THAT WAS RELEASED FROM THE CONTAINER WAS REMOVED FROM THE PAVEMENT AND ADDED TO THE LOAD.  THROUGHOUT THE CLEAN-UP OPERATION, A REPRESENTATIVE FROM THE LOCAL BOARD OF HEALTH WAS PRESENT AND WAS SAISFIED WITH THE WORK PERFORMED BY THE RESPONDERS.  THE LOAD WAS OBSERVED AND FOUND TO HAVE STOPPED LEAKING.  AT THIS POINT, THE DRIVER PROCEEDED TO DELIVER THIS SHIPMENT TO ITS ORIGINAL DESTINATION.

column168: A HARCROS TRACTOR-TRAILER DEPARTED THE DALLAS PLANT AT ABOUT 11:45 AM ON 6-26-92 TO MAKE LOCAL DELIVERIES.  THE CONTENTS OF THE TRAILER WERE: * 4-650 LB. DRUMS OF 50% CAUSTIC SODA * 2-200 LB. DRUMS OF SULFURIC ACID * 2-110 LB. DRUM OF POTASSIUM PERMANGANATE * 50-25 LB. BAGS FO FILTER POWDER * 224-100 LB. BAGS OF SODIUM SESQUICARBONATE * 1-650 LB. DRUM OF SODIUM HYPOCHLORITE * 12-150 LB. CYLINDERS OF LIQUID CHLORINE SEGREGATION OF PRODUCTS AND PLACARDING WERE IN ACCORDANCE WITH DOT REGULATIONS.  THE FOLLOWING SUMMARY IS PRIMARILY PER AN INTERVIEW WITH THE DRIVER: THE INCIDENT OCCURRED ABOUT 1.5 MILES FROM THE PLANT ON THE LOOP 12 OVERPASS CROSSING THE TRINITY RIVER.  AT ABOUT THE TIME THE TRUCK CRESTED THE OVERPASS, NORTHBOUND, (1) THE DRIVER SMELLED CHLORINE, (2) A PASSING MOTORIST STARTED HONKING HIS HORN AND MOTIONING TOWARD THE TRAILER AND (3) THE DRIVER LOOKED IN HIS REAR VIEW MIRROR AND SAW A CLOUD OF GREEN GAS COMING FROM THE TRAILER.  HE IMMEDIATELY PULLED ONTO THE SHOULDER, STOPPED, GOT OUT OF THE TRACTOR AND MOVED ABOUT 50 YARDS FROM THE TRUCK, AS THERE WAS STILL A STRONG SMELL OF CHLORINE.  A TRININTY RIVER AUTHORITY EMPLOYEE WHO WAS FAMILIAR WITH CHLORINE STOPPED TO ASSIST.  HE TOOK OUR DRIVER TO THE BOTTOM OF THE OVERPASS.  APPARENTLY, A PASSING MOTORIST HAD NOTIFIED THE AUTHORITIES.  THERE WERE SEVERAL AMBULANCES AT THAT POINT. THEY WERE TAKING PEOPLE WHO HAD DRIVEN THROUGH THE CLOUD TO THE HOSPITAL AND RELEASED.  THE DRIVER RETURNED TO THE VICININTY OF THE TRUCK UPON ARRIVAL OF THE HARCROS EMERGENCY RESPONSE TEAM. THIS BASICALLY CONCLUDES THE DRIVER'S STATEMENT. THE PLANT WAS NOTIFIED OF THE PROBLEM AT ABOUT 12:20 PM BY THE IRVING HAZMAT TEAM.  WE HAD OUR CHLOREP TEAM ON SITE BY 23:35 PM WITH THEIR EQUIPMENT AND A DRIVER, TRUCK AND PICKUP.  OUR PRIMARY CONTRACT AT THE SCENE WAS CHIEF BASSINGER OF THE CITY OF IRVING FIRE DEPARTMENT. HAZMAT PERSONNEL WERE BRIEFED ON THE CONTENTS OF THE TRAILER, LOCATION OF THE VARIOUS PRODUCTS, POTENTIAL HAZARDS, ETC.  I INFORMED THE HAZMAT PERSONNEL AND CHIEF BASSINGER THAT WE WERE CHLOREP TRAINED AND CERTIFIED, AS WELL AS FULLY EQUIPPED TO HANDLE ANY CHLORINE EMERGENCY. HAZMAT WAS NOT ALLOWING ANYONE WITHIN 150-200 YARDS OF THE TRUCK.  THEY DECLINED TO ALLOW US TO TAKE CARE OF THE PROBLEM AT THAT TIME.  RATHER THEY DID THE FOLLOWING: 1)SET UP AN EMERGENCY SHOWER/DECONTAMINATION STATION ALONG WITH SPILL CONTAINMENT IN THE MIDDLE OF THE FREEWAY, 2) MAINTAIN A BARRICADE DISTANCE OF 150-200 YARDS IN ALL DIRECTIONS AND 3) SEND TWO HAZMAT PERSONNEL TO OPEN THE TRAILER.  THESE PERSONNEL WERE EQUIPPED WITH SCBA'S, ENCAPSULATING SUITS AND TWO WAY RADIOS. UPON THEIR RETURN, WE WERE PERMITTED TO GO TO AND ENTER THE TRAILER.  TWO UNRELATED PROBLEMS WERE FOUND: (1) A 150 LB. CHLORINE CYLINDER HAD DEVELOPED A BOTTOM LEAK AND WAS ESSENTIALLY EMPTY, (2) A 200 LB SULFURIC ACID POLY DRUM HAD A HAIR LINE CRACK ABOUT 1/2" LONG AND HAD SPILLED 2-3 LBS OF ACID ON THE FLOOR OF THE TRAILER.  THIS SPILLAGE WAS ABOUT 8 FEET

ON 6/4/92, THREE TANKERS CONTAINING LOADS (MANIFEST #S 90830722, 90830726, AND 90830727 - COPIES ATTACHED) ARRIVED AT THE SSI FACILITY.  THE LOADES WERE FINGERPRINTED FOR PH, AND WERE FOUND TO BE WITHIN THE RANGE NOTED ON THE PROFILE.  THE MATERIALS WERE UNLOADED INTO A TANKER AT THE SSI FACILITY.  SMALL SCALE COMPATIBLITY TESTS PERFORMED SHOWED NO REACTION. THE TANKER CONTAINING APPROXIMATELY 2300 GALLONS WAS SITUATED WITHIN A CONTAINMENT AREA AT THE FACILITY.  AT OR AROUND 8:00 PM THE TANKER SHELL FAILED AT VARIOUS POINTS AND RELEASED MOST OF THE LOAD INTO THE CONTAINMENT AREA WITH A SMALL AMOUNT ON TO THE SOIL JUST OUSIDE THE AREA. ADDITIONALLY, A RELEASE TO THE ATMOSPHERE OCCURRED.  AN ESTIMATED TOTAL OF 2000 GALLONS WAS RELEASED.  THE SAN JOSE FIRE DEPARTMENT RESPONDED TO THE INCIDENTS.  SSI LATER COMPLETED CLEAN-UP ACTIVITIES.

column168: TRUCK BROKE DOWN IN FRONT OF BLDG WHEN COMING IN TO BE UNLOADED.  WHILE UNLOCKING TRUCK OFF ELECTRIC TAILGATE WITH A FORKLIFT WITH A DRUM HANDLER ONE DRUM WAS OVERTURNED. AS THE OVERPACK DRUM WAS BEING MOVED TO WAREHOUSE WITH A DRUM HANDLER WHICH CAUGHT THE TOP OF THE DRUM, THE LID CAME OFF AND DRUM DROPPED AND OVERTURNED SPILLING THE CONTENTS.  EITHER THE LID WAS NOT SECURE TO TOP RIM OF DRUM OR THE LOCKING WAS NOT TIGHT ENOUGH.  SPILL WAS CLEANUP AND PLACED IN DRUMS.  MAKE SURE ALL LIDS ARE SECURE AND LOCKING BOLTS ARE TIGHT BEFORE LOADING OR UNLOADING DRUMS.

column168: OUR DRIVER WAS STOPPING TO CHECK IN AT DESTINATION AND WHEN THE PRODUCT SURGED SOME SPILLED INTO THE CRASH BOX AREA AND RAN OUT THE OVERFLOW TUBE. THE SPILL AREA WAS CLEANED UP BY THE CUSTOMER.  ONE OF OUR NEARBY TERMINALS WAS CALLED AND A MECHANIC WAS DISPATCHED TO THE SCENE TO DETERMINE THE PROBLEM.  IT WAS FOUND THAT THE DOME GASKET WAS DEFECTIVE AND THIS WAS THE CAUSE OF THE SPILL.  THE GASKET WAS REPLACED AND THE REMAINDER OF THE DELIVERY WAS ACCOMPLISHED WITHOUT FURTHER PROBLEMS.

OUR DRIVER HAD BEEN IN THE PROCESS OF TRANSFERRING THE MATERIAL FOR CUSTOMER'S STORAGE FOR APPROXIMATELY 50 MINUTES WHEN HE NOTED A LEAK MIDWAY UP THE LEFT SIDE OF HIS TRAILER.  THE SHUT OFF THE PRESSURE AND BLED SAME FROM THE TRAILER.  THE CONSIGNEE DIKED THE MATERIAL THAT HAD SPILLED AND NEUTRALIZED SAME.  OUR DRIVER MADE TEMPORARY REPAIRS AND WAS ABLE TO COMPLETE THE DELIVERY.  THE TRAILER WAS REMOVED FROM SERVICE FOR REPAIR.

OUR DRIVER WAS CLEARED ON DELIVERY.  HE CONNECTED THE UNLOADING HOSES AND CHECKED THE LEVEL GAUGE ON THE CONSIGNEE'S STORAGE TANK.  HE STARTED TO TRANSFER THE MATERIAL AND AFTER ABOUT 10 MINUTES THE RELIEF VALVE ACTIVATED ON HIS TRAILER VENTING FUMES INTO THE AIR.  HE SHUT DOWN AND IN CHECKING FOR THE PROBLEM FOUND THAT THE CUSTOMER'S LEVEL GAUGE WAS GIVING A FALSE READING.

OUR DRIVER HAD BEEN CLEARED FOR DELIVERY.  HE RIGGED FOR DRUM UNLOADING AND PROCEEDED TO PUMP THE MATERIAL.  WHEN THE RECEIVER SHUT OFF THE NOZZLE AFTER FILLING THE 1ST DRUM THE BACK PRESSURE CAUSED THE HOSE AT THE DISCHARGE SIDE OF THE PUMP TO BURST.  OUR DRIVER SHUT DOWN IMMEDIATELY. WHEN THE CONSIGNEE CHECKED THE MATERIAL IN THE DRUM IT APPEARED TO BE CONTAMINATED AND THE LOAD WAS THEREFORE REJECTED.  THE SPILL WAS CLEANED UP BY THE CONSIGNEE.

RIGHT REAR WHEELS OF TANKER FELL OFF THE SHOULDER CAUSING THE ENTIRE UNIT TO PULL ONTO THE SIDE OF THE ROADWAY.  ENTIRE UNIT THEN OVERTURNED, SLID 120 FEET, STOPPED AND THE TANK RUPTURED AND BURST INTO FLAMES.  THE OPREATOR MANAGED TO EXIT THE UNIT BEFORE THE EXPLOSION. AGENCIES THAT ASSISTED ARE AS FOLLOWS: STATE FIRE MARSHALL, KENTUCKY E.P.C. RESPONSE TEAM, STATE HIGHWAY DEPARTMENT, R.E.C.C., G.T.E. AND ALPHA ENVIRONMENTAL, INC.  ALPHA ENVIRONMENTAL, INC. IS IN CHARGE OF THE CLEANUP OPERATIONS.

column168: THE DRIVER DISCOVERED A WHEEL SEAL LEAKING ON HIS TRACTOR AND LOCATED A GARAGE IN ENTERPRISE, AL, THAT COULD REPAIR THE WHEEL SEAL.  THEY DID NOT HAVE SPACE FOR HIM TO PARK THE TRACTOR AND TRAILER SO HE DISCONNECTED THE TRAILER (WHICH WAS PATRIALLY LOADED) AT ANOTHER LOCATION (630 GLOVER AVE) AND WENT TO THE REPAIR FACILITY.  WHEN THE TRACTOR WAS REPAIRED, THE DRIVER WENT BACK TO PICK UP THE TANK TRAILER WHICH BY THEN WAS LEANING TO ONE SIDE.  HE CALLED THE SAME REPAIR FACILITY FOR ASSISTANCE.  THE SHOP OPERATOR CAME WITH WRECKER WITH THE INTENT TO PICK UP THE TRAILER SUFFICIENTLY TO ALLOW IT TO BE HOOKED ONTO THE TRACTOR.  BUT BEFORE ANY ACTION COULD BE TAKEN, THE LANDING GEAR DAMAGED ONE UNLOADING PIPE, INCLUDING THE EMERGENCY SAFETY VALVE ACTUATING MECHANISM.  THIS ACTON PARTIALLY OPENED THE EMERGENCY SAFETY VALVE AND A PART OF THE CONTENTS IN THAT COMPARTMENT LEAKED ONTO THE GROUND BECAUSE THE UNLOADING PIPE WAS BROKEN.  THE DRIVER IMMEDIATELY NOTIFIED THE FIRE DEPARTMENT.  APPROPRIATE EMERGENCY RESPONSE UNITS ARRIVED, CORDONED OFF THE AREA AND EVAUCATED NEARBY BUSINESSES.  AFTER THE INITIAL EMERGENCY RESPONSE, ACTION WAS TAKEN TO REMOVE THE TRACTOR/TRAILER FROM THE SITE OF THE INCIDENT AND CLEAN UP PROCEDURES WERE IMPLEMENTED BY A HAZARDOUS WASTE CONTRACTOR TO CLEAN UP AND REMOVE THE CONTAMINATED SOIL.

column168: OP CENTER REPORTED A LTC IN GLENWOOD, WV.  CAR WAS SPOTTED LEAKING BY CITIZEN.  FIRE DEPT HAD IMMEDIATE AREA EVACUATED (ROAD CLOSED).  I TALKED TO DUPONT (SHIPPER) WHO WAS SENDING A RESPONSE TEAM.  TEAM RESPONDED AND REPAIRED VALVE STEM ON SIDE OF SAFETY RELIEF VALVE.  CAR WAS RELEASED AND SENT TO DESTINATION.
OP CENTER REPORTED LEAKING TANK CAR IN WALBRIDGE, OHIO YARD.  I CONTACTED SHIPPER WHO RESPONDED NEXT DAY AND TIGHTENED ALL MANWAY COVER BOLTS.  CAR WAS RELEASED TO DESTINATION.

OP CENTER REPORTED LTC IN LIMA YARD.  I CONTACTED YARDMASTER WHO STATED THAT A BRAKEMAN SMELLED AMMONIA COMING FROM A CUT OF 6 CARS.  THE FIRE DEPT RESPONDED AND BP CHEMICAL THEIR MUTUAL AID RESPONDED.  UPON INSPECTION THEY FOUND THE PACKING ON THE GAUGING DEVICE LOOSE AND THE LIQUID LINE OPEN SLIGHTLY WITH NO PLUG INSERTED.  THEY INSERTED THE PLUG AND TIGHTENED ALL THE FITTINGS.  CAR WAS THEN RELEASED TO DESTINATION.

OP CENTER REPORTED LTC IN RUSHMAN YARD.  I CONTACTED SHIPPER, THEY WERE NOT VERY HELPFUL.  I CONTACTED TOM DAVIS OF BOE - WHO RESPONDED AND REPLACED RUPTURE DISC.  CAR WAS RELEASED AT 1835 THAT EVENING.

OP CENTER REPORTED CAR LEAKING IN GRAND RAPIDS.  I CONTACTED YARD AND YARDMASTER STATED THAT CAR HAD BEEN VENTING BUT NOW HAS STOPPED.  CAR WAS INSPECTED FOLLOWING DAY AND NOTHING WRONG COULD BE FOUND.  CAR MOVED TO DESTINATION THERE IN GRAND RAPIDS.

column168: OUR DRIVER WAS ENROUTE TO HIS DESTINATION WHEN HE WAS STOPPED BY THE HIGHWAY PATROLMAN SINCE HE OBSERVED SMOKE COMING FROM THE BOTTOM OF OUR TRAILER.  THE UNIT WAS SECURED ON THE SHOULDER OF THE ROADWAY AND IN CHECKING IT WAS DETERMINED THAT THERE WAS A MINOR DRIP FROM THE SUMP AREA. THE RESPONSE AGENCIES WERE NOTIFIED AND ARRIVED AT THE SITE AS WELL AS REPRESENTATIVES FROM THE CONSIGNEE'S FACILITY WHICH WAS LOCATED A SHORT DISTANCE AWAY.  THE RESPONSE PERSONNEL ATTEMPTED TO TIGHTEN THE BOLTS AT THE FLANGE BUT THIS DID NOT CORRECT THE SITUATION.  A RUBBER BOOT WAS THEN ATTACHED TO THE SUMP AREA TO CONTAIN THE DRIP AND THE UNIT WAS ESCORTED TO THE CONSIGNEE'S PLANT AND THE MATERIAL WAS UNLOADED.  INSPECTION OF THE TRAILER REVEALED THAT THE GASKET AT THE SUMP FLANGE WAS DEFECTIVE ALLOWING THE LEAK.  THE TRAILER WAS REMOVED FROM SERVICE FOR REPAIRS.  THE SPILL AREA WAS CLEANED UP BY AN OUTSIDE CONTRACTOR THAT HAD BEEN SUMMONED AND STOOD BY THROUGHOUT THE INCIDENT.

A H.T.S. DRIVER WAS OFF LOADING AT A TEXACO PLANT IN GLENHAM, NY.  THEY THOUGHT THEY HAD THE PUMP IN THE RIGHT POSITION TO UNLOAD, BUT THE PUMP WAS ACTUALLY IN THE LOADING POSITION.  THE TRAILER PRESSURED UP AND BLEW PRODUCT OUT OF THE VENT.  APPROX 50 GALLONS OF I-H CAT DIESEL WAS SPILLED WHICH WAS CLEANED UP BY TEXACO'S RESPONSE TEAM.  THE CONTROLS ON THE TRUCK HAVE BEEN RECONFIGURED AND REMARKED TO PREVENT THIS FROM HAPPENING AGAIN.

column168: WHILE LOADING THE AIRCRAFT, A SULFUOUS SMELL, FOLLOWED BY GRAY SMOKE WAS NOTICED IN THE AIRCRAFT CARGO BIN BY THE RAMP AGENTS LOADING THE FLIGHT. THE FUELER WAS IMMEDIATELY ADVISED TO DISCONNECT FROM THE AIRCRAFT AND PULL AWAY.  A RAMP AGENT THEN WENT UP THE JETWAY AND ADVISED THE CAPTAIN AND THE OPERATIONS AGENT.  THE CAPTAIN HAD THE CREW DEPLANED, THERE WERE NO PASSENGERS ON BOARD.  THE OPERATIONS AGENCY CALLED THE OPERATIONS OFFICE AND ADVISED THEM OF THE SITUATION.  THE OPERATIONS OFFICE CALLED THE AIRPORT CONTROL CENTER AND DISPATCH.  THE AIRPORT CONTROL CENTER DISPATCHED THE CLARK COUNTY FIRE DEPT. AND THE LAS VEGAS METROPOLITAN POLICE DEPT., BOTH ARE LOCATED ON THE FIELD.  THE RAMP AGENTS IMMEDIATELY STARTED  TO OFF LOAD THE AIRCRAFT CARGO BIN AND THIS WAS COMPLETED BY THE TIME THE FIRE DEPT AND POLICE DEPT ARRIVED ON THE SCENE.  NO CAUSE OR DAMAGE WAS DETECTED IN THE CARGO BIN.  THE POLICE DEPT DISPATCHED A BOMB DOG TO SEARCH THE LUGGAGE.  THE DOG FOUND NOTHING.  THE LUGGAGE WAS THEN PLACED THROUGH A MOBILE E-SCAN UNIT PROVIDED BY THE CLARK COUNTY DEPT OF AVIATION.  THIS ALSO DETECTED NO CAUSE FOR THE ODOR AND SMOKE.  IT WAS THEN DETERMINED BY DISPATCH AND THE OPERATIONS DEPT TO HAVE ALL LUGGAGE POSITIVELY CLAIMED BY THE PASSENGERS AND WAS THEN DETERMINED BY DISPATCH PRESENCE.  DURING THIS PROCEDURE A GARMENT BAG WITH SEVERAL SMALL BURN HOLES IN THE LOWER LEFT CORNER WAS FOUND. column168: THE PCB SPILL WAS THE RESULT OF A SPILL FROM A LEAKING CAPACITOR CONTAINED IN A CRATE. THE SPILL OCCURRED ON JUNE 26, 1992. THE CLEANUP TOOK PLACE IMMEDIATELY ON THE SAME DATE AS LISTED ABOVE. THE SPILL OCCURRED AT THE VERY REAR END OF A SEMI TRAILER. PRE-CLEANUP SAMPLING WAS NOT NECESSARY AS THE SPILL BOUNDARY WAS CLEARLY VISIBLE AND DEFINED. THERE WAS NO RELEASE TO SOIL OR THE ENVIRONMENT. IT WAS AGREED THAT MORE THOROUGH INSPECTIONS BY OUR DRIVERS WILL TAKE PLACE AT THE TIME OF PICK-UP TO INSURE THAT THE MATERIAL IS PROPERLY PACKAGED. THESE INSPECTIONS SHOULD HELP PREVENT ANY OCCURRENCES OF THIS TYPE IN THE FUTURE. THE INFORMATION ABOVE WAS STATED TO ME BY RICHARD DIEKMAN UPON HIS RETURN TO ST. PAUL. HE ATTESTED THAT HE HAD ADHERED TO ALL EPA CLEANUP REQUIREMENTS DURING THE PCB SPILL CLEANUP.

D/S RON WIEGMANN WAS BREAKING OUR INBOUND FREIGHT OFF TRAILER 415-6082 AND HE SMELLED AN ODOR WHEN BRINGING OF THE PALLET THAT CONTAINED THE HAZARDOUS MATERIAL.  WHEN HE GOT IS TO THE BACK OF THE TRAILER HE HAD DISCOVERED THAT THE CORNERS OF ONE BOX WAS CRUSHED.  HE TOOK THE BOX OFF PALLET AND LOOKED IN AND FOUND THAT ONE CONTAINER WAS LEAKING AND ONE WAS CRUSHED.  HE PUT CONTAINERS ON CARDBOARD WITH FLOOR DRY.  I PHONED SAFETY SUPERVISOR BOB TARRANT AND ADVISED HIM OF THE LEAKAGE.  HE TOLD ME TO GET IN TOUCH WITH THE SHIPPER TO FIND OUT DISPOSITION OF DAMAGE.  MIKE MCKEE AT PITTMAN MOORE SAID THEY WOULD TAKE CAR OF THE DISPOSAL I INFORMED MIKE THAT I WOULD HAVE TO GET IN TOUCH WITH MY SAFETY SUPERVISOR.  I TALKED TO BOB TARRANT AND HE CALLED AND TALKED TO MIKE.  BOB CALLED ME BACK AND SAID MIKE WOULD BE GETTING IN TOUCH WITH ME TO LET ME KNOW WHEY THEY WOULD BE HERE TO PICK UP LEAKAGE.  MR. BOB TARRANT SHIPPER WOULD BE TAKING CARE OF DISPOSAL.

SENIOR SPECIAL AGENT/HAZARDOUS MATERIALS (SSA/HM) T.M. ROBINSON WAS NOTIFIED MECHNICAL MAINTENANCE, JIM OSBURN THAT TANK CAR NATX 22604 WAS LEAKING.  THE CAR WAS BEING DELIVERED TO UNION CARBIDE IN TAFT, LA.  MR. OSBURN RESPONDED TO THE INCIDENT AND INSPECTION DETERMINED THAT A SMALL AMOUNT OF PRODUCT WAS LEAKING FROM A CRACK ON THE BOTTOM OF THE TANK AT THE "A" END ON THE LEFT SIDE WHERE TANK IS WELED TO THE DRAFT SILL.  MR. OSBURN SPOKE WITH PLANT PERSONNEL AND UNION CARBIDE PERSONNEL UNLOADED THE CAR.

SENIOR SPECIAL AGENT/HAZARDOUS MATERIALS (SSA/HM) G.B. REEDER WAS NOTIFIED THAT A SWITCHMAN HAD BEEN SPLASHED WITH ACID AT COADY YARD.  SSA/HM REEDER RESPONDED AND UPON ARRIVAL NOTED L. HARRISON HAD BEEN SPLASHED BY CAR RPBX 23122 AND HAD ACID BURNS ON HIS LEFT FOREARM.  EMPLOYEE WAS TREATED BY MR. MIRANDA AND HAD ONE DAY OF REPORTABLE LOST TIME.  SSA/HM REEDER'S INSPECTION DETERMINED THAT THE LEAK WAS CAUSED BY A MISALIGNED GASKET ON THE FILL HOLE.  LYONDELL SUPPLIED A REPLACEMENT GASKET AND SSA/HM REEDER AND BRIAN SOSSAMAN REPAIRED THE CAR.  CAR WAS THEN RELEASED FOR FURTHER MOVEMENT.

SENIOR SPECIAL AGENT/HAZARDOUS MATERIALS (SSA/HM) T.H. SMITH AND SPECIAL AGENT/HAZARDOUS MATERIALS (SA/HM) R.L. CERDA WERE NOTIFIED BY SPECIAL AGENT NARVAEZ OF A STRONG ODOR FROM INTERMODAL TANK SCXU 872224 AS IT WAS BEING UNLOADED AT THE PORT LAREDO FACILITY.  THERE WAS NO VISIBLE LEAK NOTED.  SA/HM R.L. CERDA AND THE ATOCHEM RESPONSE TEAM RESPONDED TO THE SCENE.  INSPECTION DETERMINED THAT THE HEAT HAD INCREASED THE PRESSURE IN THE TANK AND THE MANWAY NUTS HAD LOOSENED ALLOWING VAPOR TO ESCAPE.  THE MANWAY WAS TIGHTENED AND THE PRESSURE WAS REMOVED FROM THE INTERMODAL WITH THE AID OF A TANK TRUCK.  TANK WAS THEN RELEASED FOR FURTHER MOVEMENT. CHEMTREC WAS NOTIFIED OF THE INCIDENT.

THIS LOAD ORIGINATED AT THE IMR PLANT LOCATED AT PLATTSBURG, NY CONSISTING OF 73 CASES, 1,548 LBS OF SMOKELESS POWDER FOR SMALL ARMS, DESTINED TO GARY BAYLESS AT SAN BERNARDINO, CA.  THIS LOAD TRAVELED TO THE C I WHITTEN TERMINAL SAFE HAVEN AND WAS TRANSFERRED AND CONSOLIDATED WITH A WHITTEN TRUCK GOING WEST, LOADLOCKS THAT WERE USED TO BLOCK THIS LOAD, APPARENTLY FAILED, SEVERAL CASES OF SMOKELESS POWDER FELL TO THE FLOOR OF THE TRAILER, THE LIDS ON TWO CANS VIBRATED OFF SPILLING 12 GRAMS OF POWDER ON THE FLOOR.  THE CONTAMINATED POWDER WAS CLEANED UP, REMOVED AND PROPERLY DISPOSED.  THE LOAD WAS RELOCKED AND CONTINUED ON WITHOUT FURTHER INCIDENT.  COMPANY PERSONNEL INVOLVED HAVE BEEN RETRAINED IN THE PROPER METHOD OF BLOCKING AND BRACING OF HAZARDOUS MATERIALS.
column172: Metal can, capacity 7 gallons or less

column168: AT APPROX 21:00 ON THE 10TH OF JUNE TIM TANNER WAS TAKING A INVENTORY OF ALITALIA IMPORT FREIGHT ON OUR RACK SYSTEM. IN LOCATION SS005 HE PROCEEDED TO MOVE A BOX I ORDER TO READ THE AWB NR, AS THE BOX WAS MOVED A SUBSTANCE FLOWED OUT OF THE PACKAGE SPILLING ONTO SEVERAL PIECES OF FREIGHT AND THE GROUND, HE THEN INFORMED HIS SUPERVISOR (MYSELF). AT THIS TIME TIM AND I INSPECTED THE SITUATION AND TRIED TO CONTAIN THE SPILL. NOT REALIZING THE HAZARD OF THE CONTENTS WE TRIED TO CLEAN THE SPILL, AT THIS TIMEWE NOTICED THE POISON LABEL. I INSTRUCTED TIM TO LEAVE THE SPILL ALONE UNTIL WE WHERE SURE AS TO WHAT TO DO. AT THIS TIME I INFORMED MY FELLOW SUPERVISOR SCOTT KOWALCZEK, AND BOTH OF US INVESTIGATED ON THE CONTENTS AND PROCEDURE IN CASE OF SPILL. WE CONSULTED THE EMERGENCY RESPONSE BOOK, WHICH INSTRUCTED US TO RINSE ANY BODY PARTS WITH WATER FOR SEVERAL MINUTES, WHICH WE ALL DID. I THEN CALLED THE EMERGENCY RESPONSE TOLL FREE NUMBER FROM THE BOOK AND INFORMED THEM OF THE SITUATION. THEY INSTRUCTED ME TO HAVE EVERYONE IN CONTACT WITH THE CONTENTS TO RINSE WITH WATER, AND TO STAY CLEAR OF THE SPILL. THEY THEN INFORMED ME THAT THEY WOULD FAX ME DOCUMENTS THAT WHERE IN TURN TO BE HANDED OVER TO THE FIRE DEPT WHICH I WAS TO CALL. I INFORMED AT THIS TIME MY TERMINAL MNGR ROBERT GENTILE WHO CALLED THE CHICAGO FIRE DEPT AT OHARE FIELD. THE CHICAGO FIRE DEPT REMOVED THE LEAKING BOX ALONG WITH SEVERAL OTHER PIECES OF FREIGHT ON WHICH THE CHEMICAL HAD SPILLED ONTO, AND PROCEEDED TO CLEAN ALL SPILLAGE FROM THE AREA. TIM TANNER, SCOTT KOWALCZEK AND MYSELF DENIED MEDICAL TREATMENT, BUT HAD BLOOD PRESSURE, HEART RATE CHECKED AT THE SCENE.

BE ADVISED THAT ON 6/10/92 HAZMAT DISPATCH RECEIVED A CALL VIA RADIO FROM GROUND 35 (LYNN POEPPLEMAN, SORT SUPERVISOR) STATING SHE HAD A SPILL IN ALPHA BUILDING, ENTER A-6, CODE OAK, OF THE TERTIARY.  THIS SPILL WAS LOCATED ON THE GROUNDS OF AIRBORN EXPRESS INC., 145 HUNTER DRIVE, WILMINGTON, OH 45177.  CERT 13 (JEFFREY A. HOSTETLER) ILN HAZMAT COORDINATOR AND CERT 08 PART-TIME HAZMAT TECHNICIAN (NEIL VANSAUN) RESPONDED AND ON SCENE ON 0306.  GROUND 35 WAS ON THE SCENE AND STATED THAT THE EXPRESS PLASTIC ENVELOPE WAS EXPANDING AND A WHITE LIQUID HAD BREECHED THE SEAL.  UPON INVESTIGATION AN ENVELOPE AIRWAY BILL ORD 344129446 OAK WAS OPENED AND A METAL CONTAINER WAS FOUND TO HAVE DISCHARGED.  THIS CONTAINER STATED THAT THE PRODUCT WAS A FLAMMABLE MATERIAL AND WAS UNDER PRESSURE.  THE PRODUCT WAS CONTAINED AND ALL OTHER FREIGHT CLEANED OF RESIDUE.  THIS SHIPMENT WAS REMOVED FROM THE AREA, BAGGED AND HELD IN ILN.  CLEAR OF SCENE AT 0314.  DESCRIPTION AS FOLLOWS: OUTER PACKAGING: WHITE AIRBORNE EXPRESS PLASTIC SHIPPING ENVELOPE.  AIRWAY BILL STATED--FROM: ALBERTO CULVER, 2525 W. ARMITAGE AVE., MELROSE PARK, IL 60160--TO: BEAUTY FACTOR, 900 ALADDIN AVE., SAN LEANDRO,CA 94577, ORD 34129446 OAK.  THE OUTER PACKAGING WAS NOT MARKED, LABELED OR OTHERWISE CERTIFIED TO INDICATE THE CONTENTS WERE REGULATED AS A HAZARDOUS MATERIAL. INNER PACKAGING: BROWN BUBBLE WRAP ENVELOPE.  NO MARKINGS OR LABELS. CONTENTS ARE AS FOLLOWS: 2-HAIR SCIENCE CONDITIONER, 7 OZ IN FOIL PACKETS 1-HAIR SCIENCE SHAMPOO, 16 OZ WHITE PLASTIC CONTAINER W/SCREW TYPE CLOSURE. 1-HAIR SCIENCE SPRITZ, 8 OZ WHITE PLASTIC CONTAINER PUMP TYPE SPRAY MECHANISM, SCREW TYPE CLOSURE WITH NO POSITIVE MEANS TO SECURE.  STATED ON LABEL "FLAMMABLE". 1-HAIR SCIENCE MOUSSE, 13.5 OZ WHITE METAL CONTAINER WITH SPRAY TYPE MECHANISM.  PLASTIC CAP COVERING NOZZLE HAD COME OFF AND AIDED IN DISCHARGE.  NO POSITIVE MEANS TO SECURE CLOSURE.  STATED "FLAMMABLE UNDER PRESSURE". APPROXIMATE LOSS OF PRODUCT--13 OZ.  ALSO ENCLOSED IN THIS SHIPMENT WERE NUMEROUS ADVERTISEMENTS.  THIS SHIPMENT WAS HELD AND IS LOCATED IN THE ILN HAZMAT SECURITY CAGE UNDER LOCK AND KEY PENDING AN FAA INVESTIGATION.

ON 6-11-92, SORT SUPERVISOR, TONY BUTCHER, REPORTED A SHIPMENT LEAKING IN THE MAIN SORT.  UPON ARRIVAL ON THE SCENE, I, TONY FRYE, CHECKED THE SHIPMENT IN QUESTION.  THIS WAS A FIBREBOARD BOX AND ONE SIDE OF IT WAS VERY WET.  I USED SOME PH PAPER TO SEE IF THIS WAS AN ACID OR A BASE.  THE PH PAPER READ NEUTRAL.  I OPENED THE FIBREBOARD BOX AND FOUND INSIDE THREE AEROSOL RECEPTICLES.  ALSO INSIDE THE FIBREBOARD BOX WAS SEVERAL OTHER MISC. AUTO COSMETICS.  THE AEROSOL RECEPTICLES DID NOT LEAK.  TWO OF THE AEROSOLS WERE "TUFF STUFF", 8 OZ EACH AND THE THIRD WAS "ELIMINATOR II, ENGINE DEGREASER" AND IT CONTAINED 15 OZS.  LISTED ON THE LABEL OF THE ENGINE DEGREASER WAS THE FOLLOWING: "DANGER: EXTREMELY FLAMMABLE".  THERE WERE NO MARKINGS LABELS OR PROPER CERTIFICATION ACCOMPANYING THIS SHIPMENT TO INDICATE THAT ITS CONTENTS WERE REGULATED AS HAZARDOUS MATERIALS.  THIS SHIPMENT IS AT THE HAZMAT SORT, IN THE SECURITY CAGE UNDER LOCK AND KEY, PENDING FAA INVESTIGATION.

column168: EASTERN DRIVER WILLIAM GULLEDGE 111 MADE A GASOLINE DELIVERY TO CUSTOMER ACCOUNT.  CUSTOMER TANK LOCATION DOES NOT GIVE OPTIMUM DRAINAGE DUE TO INCLINE AT FILL AREA.  DRIVER HAD BEEN TRAINED TO RETURN HEELS TO SUPPLY TERMINALS AND TO DRAIN DRY THE CARGO TANKBEFORE RELOADING ANY INCOMPATIBLE PRODUCT(S).  INSTEAD OF FOLLOWING POLICY.  DRIVER CAUSED PRODUCT HEEL (GASOLINE) TO BE OFFLOADED INTO ROADSIDE DITCH.  THIS WAS DONE ON 6-22-92 AND REPORTED BY FAUQUIER SHERIFFS DEPT. TO EASTERN ON 6-24-92.  CLEANUP EFFORTS BEGAN IMMEDIATELY AND WERE CONCLUDED ON 6-25-92 TO THE SATISFACTION OF THE STATE OF VA.  DEPUTY CUNO ANDERSON OF THE FAUQUIER SHERIFFS DEPT IS INVESTIGATING THIS MATTER ALONG WITH VA STATE POLICE POSSIBLE CRIMINAL CHARGES MAY BE BROUGHT AGAINST MR. GULLEDGE. ALL REQUIRED NOTIFICATIONS WERE MADE TO APPROPRIATE AGENCIES IMMEDIATELY UPON NOTIFICATION OF A SPILL INCIDENT.

column168: SPECIAL AGENT/HAZARDOUS MATERIALS (SM/HM) R.L. CERDA WAS NOTIFIED THAT TRAILER XTRZ 255580 WAS LEAKING PRODUCT AT PORT LAREDO.  SA/HM CERDA RESPONDED AND INSPECTION DETERMINED THAT THE CENTER BLOCKING HAD FAILED AND THAT ONE DRUM HAD BEEN PUNCTURED.  PATTY SMITH OF CLARKE INTERNATIONAL NOTIFIED CARL MARKET OF DIACHEM (SHIPPER) AND DECISION WAS MADE TO RESTACK AND BLOCK CAR.  SA/HM CERDA RESTACKED DRUMS AND CONTACT SSA/HM T.H. SMITH FOR ASSISTANCE.  AGENTS PLACED PUNCTURED DRUM IN OVERPACK, NEUTRALIZED CAR, AND BLOCKED THE TRAILER FOR FUTURE MOVEMENT. JEFF BOTWINICK OF CHEMTREC, JAQUES SAVARD OF CANUTECH (CANADA), AND CARL MARKET OF DIACHEM WEREALL NOTIFIED OF THE INCIDENT.

column62: Loose Closure, Component, or Device; Defective Component or Device
column168: SPECIAL AGENT/HAZARDOUS MATERIALS (SA/HM) F.H. LERCH WAS NOTIFIED THAT CAR PLMX 33349 WAS LEAKING AND WAS LOCATED IN WEST BOWL TRACK 27.  SA/HM LERCH RESPONDED AND NOTED A STRONG AMMONIA ODOR AND A SMALL VAPOR CLOUD FROM THE PROTECTIVE HOUSING OF THE TANK CAR.  SA/HM LERCH REMOVED THE INTACT BN SEAL HX-150823 FROM THE HOUSING AND INSPECTION DETERMINED LIQUID AND VAPOR RELEASE FROM THE LIQUID VALVE FLANGES WHICH WERE LOOSE.  THE VAPOR VALVE FLANGE, SAFETY VALVE FLANGE, AND SAFETY PLUGS TO BOTH VAPOR AND LIQUID VALVES WERE ALL FOUND TO BE LOOSE.  THE PACKING GLAND NUT TO THE VAPOR VALVE WAS LOOSE AND THE THREADS HAD BEEN STRIPPED.  SA/HM LERCH TIGHTENED ALL FITTINGS AND SMALL LEAK COULD STILL BE DETECTED FROM THE PACKING GLAND NUT AND ONE OTHER AREA WHICH COULD NOT BE PINPOINTED.  CAR WAS BAD ORDERED AND SET OUT FOR OFF LOADING.  MR. JACK CURRY, MANAGER OF HAZARDOUS MATERIALS AND SAFETY FOR FARMLAND INDUSTRIES, WAS BRIEFED OF THE INCIDENT BE ADVISED THAT DISPATCH TRUCKS FOR OFF LOADING OF PRODUCT WOULD BE SENT. PRODUCT WAS TRANSFERRED AND CAR WAS TENCILED BAD ORDER, RED TAGGED, AND ROUTED BACK TO SHIP FOR REPAIRS. JEFF BOTWINICK OF CHEMTREC, BILL INGRAM OF NEBRASKA STATE PATROL, AND BILL CURRY OF FARMLAND INDUSTRIES WERE NOTIFIED OF THE INCIDENT.

column42: PETROLEUM GASES, LIQUEFIED OR LIQUEFIED PETROLEUM GAS
column58: Auxiliary Valve; Piping or Fittings; Vapor Valve
column168: SENIOR SPECIAL AGENT/HAZARDOUS MATERIALS (SSA/HM) T.M. ROBINSON WAS NOTIFIED BY SSA MILLER THAT TANK CAR TILX 300703 WAS LEAKING PRODUCT IN THE UP SWITCHING YARD IN AVONDALE.  SSA MILLER REPORTED A SIGNIFICANT LIQUID LEAK FORM THE TOP WITH A VISIBLE VAPOR.  SSA/HM RESPONDED AND UPON ARRIVAL THE CAR WAS NO LONGER LEAKING LIQUID.  SSA/HM ROBINSON AND TECHNICIAN BLAINE BRAUD OF AMERICAN CYANAMID INSPECTED THE CAR AND DETERMINED THAT THE SAFETY RELIEF VALVE HAD RESEATED BUT THAT ONE OF THE "O" RINGS HAD BLOWN OUT.  AS A RESULT, A SMALL LEAK STILL CONTINUED. PRESSURE WAS 190 PSIG AND OUTAGE WAS 7 INCHES.  CAR WAS GIVEN A PRIORITY MOVEMENT TO AMERICAN CYANAMID (FIVE MILES) FOR UNLOADING AND REPAIR OF THE SAFETY RELIEF VALVE. CHEMTREC, THE LOUISIANA STATE POLICES, THE LOUISIANA DEPARTMENT OF ENVIRONMENTAL QUALITY, AMERICAN CYANAMID, AND THE BRIDGE CITY VOLUNTEER FIRE DEPARTMENT WERE ALL NOTIFIED OF THE INCIDENT.

SENIOR SPECIAL AGENT/HAZARDOUS MATERIAL T.M. ROBINSON WAS NOTIFIED THAT A TRAIN CREW DETECTED A STRONG ODOR OF AMMONIA FROMT ANK CAR UTLX 99071. SSA/HM ROBINSON RESPONDED AND INSPECTION DETERMINED THAT THERE WAS A SMALL VAPOR LEAK FROM BENEATH THE PRESSURE PLATE AT THE MANWAY NOZZLE.  SSA/HM ROBINSON WAS ABLE TO TIGHTEN SEVERAL OF THE PRESSURE PLATES BOLTS WHICH SLOWED THE LEAK BUT DID NOT COMPLETELY STOP THE LEAK.  CAR WAS TANK BACK TO TRIAD CHEMICAL PLANT AND UNLOADED SO THAT APPROPRIATE REPAIRS COULD BE MADE. NOTIFICATION WERE MADE TO CHEMTREC, THE LOUISIANA STATE POLICE, LOUISIANA DEPARTMENT OF ENVIRONMENTAL QUALITY, LOCAL SHERIFF'S OFFICE AND DONALDSON VILLE FIRE DEPARTMENT.

SENIOR SPECIAL AGENT/HAZARDOUS MATERIALS (SSA/HM) T.M. ROBINSON WAS NOTIFIED THAT UTLX 200194 WAS LEAKING LIQUID FROM THE TOP OF THE CAR.  CAR WAS ISOLATED AND SSA/HM ROBINSON RESPONDED.  INSPECTION DETERMINED THAT THE PLUG FOR THE LIQUID VALVE WAS NOT SECURE AND THE VALVE, A TWO INCH BALL VALVE, WAS NOT COMPLETELU CLOSED.  A BUILD UP OF INTERNAL PRESSURE WAS FORCING LIQUID UP THE EDUCTION PIPE AND OUT THE VALVE.  AFTER RELIEVING THE PRESSURE, SSA/HM ROBINSON PROPERLY CLOSED THE LIQUID VALVE AND SECURED THE PLUG WHICH STOPPED THE LEAK.  SSA/HM ROBINSON WAS ASSISTED ON THE SCENE BY THE ADDIS VOLUNTEER FIRE DEPARTMENT. CHEMTREC, ASHLAND CHEMICAL, LOUISIANA STATE POLICE THE LOUISIAN DEPARTMENT OF ENVIRONMENTAL QUALITY WERE ALL NOTIFIED OF THE INCIDENT.

SENIOR SPECIAL AGENT/HAZARDOUS MATERIALS (SSA/HM) C. E. ZERWECK WASNOTIFIED THAT A SLIGHT SMELL OF AMMONIA WAS NOTED AROUND TANK CAR NDYX 334324 AT CENTENNIAL  YARD.  SSA/HM ZERWECK RESPONDED.  INSPECTION DETERMINED THAT THE VALVE ON THE GAUGING DEVICE WAS LOOSE .  VALVE WAS TIGHTENED WHICH STOPPED THE LEAK AND ODOR DISSIPATED. CHEMTEC WAS NOTIFIED OF THE INCIDENT.

LOW NOTED TANK CAR FLIX 8019 HAD THE SAMPLE TUBE VALVE BROKEN OFF FLUSH AT THE MANWAY PLATE AND VAPOR WAS LEAKING FROM THE AREA. SSA/HM LOW USED LEAD WOOL AND METAL PASTE TO STOP THE LEAK.  THE CAR WAS TAGGED DECALS "DO NOT LOAD RETURN TO HOME SHOP" WAS PLACED OM BOTH SIDE OF THE CAR WITH AN "X" ON THE AREA OF THE BROKEN VALVE. MARVIN VAN IVES OF COASTAL CHEM WAS NOTIFIED AND ADVISED OF THE INCIDENT. CAR WAS THEN BILLED TO FARMLANDS SHOP.  HOAG, NE.

CONTAINER FOUND WITH SLOW DRIP FROM BOTTOM FLOOR SEAM AFTER DE-RAMPED IN CSXT'S N CHARLESTON YARD.  LOCAL CONTACTOR (FENN-VAC) SECURED DRUMS AND PLASTIC ORDER TRAILER AND DECONTAMINATED RAMP ASPHALT (ABOUT 1 CUP OF MOT'L SPILLED).  CONTTRACTOR THEN CLEANED AND TRANSLOADED DRUMS TO 48' TRAILER, OVERPACKING 3 LEAKING DRUMS, FOR RETURN TO SHIPPER.  ESTIMATE 10 GALLONS TOTAL MAY HAVE LEAKED FROM THESE THREE (3) DRUMS, BUT LESS THAN 1 GALLON OF THIS WAS OUTSIDE OF CONTAINER.  DRUMS LEAKED AT PINHOLES RUBBED IN RTMS DUE TO LACK OF BLOCKING (BRACING) IN CONTAINER.  ORIGINATING SHIPPER CONTACT:  WADE MURPHY 800/828-7940, FIRST CHEMICAL, PASAGOULD, MS.

column58: Auxiliary Valve; Bottom Outlet Valve; Piping or Fittings
column168: MANAGER HAZARDOUS MATERIAL EMERGENCY RESPONSE, R. M.  STINE, WAS NOTIFIED BY MR. DALE FRAIZER, MANAGER OF YARD OPERATIONS, ADVISING THAT FRA HAZARDOUS MATERIAL INSPECTOR PAT PATTON HAD MADE INSPECTION OF TRAIN NLNP-08 ON MAIN LINE AT PARSON, KANSAS AND NOTED CAR ACFX 84548 LEAKING PRODUCT FROM THE BOTTOM OUTLET CAP AT RATE OF ONE DROP PER 25 SECONDS. CAR FOREMAN O. R. GARDENHIRE WAS ON THGE SCENE AND CORRECTED THE FOLLOWING EXCEPTIONS.  THE TOP OPERATING BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE WAS TIGHTENED 1/4TH OF A TURN WHICH SEATED THE VALVE AND LEAK WAS STOPPED.  THE PACKING GLAND NUT ON THE TOP OPERATING VALVE WAS TIGHTENED.  THE TWO INCH PLUG IN THE BOTTOM OUTLET CAP, AS WELL AS THE OUTLET CAP WERE NOT WRENCH TIGHT. JIM COOPER OF CHEMTREC, LARRY KNOCHE OF KANSAS ENVIRONMENTAL WERE NOTIFIED OF THE INCIDENT.

column42: HYDROGEN, PEROXIDE, AQUEOUS SOLUTIONS WITH MORE THAN 40 PERCENT BUT NOT MORE THAN 60 PERCENT HYDROGEN PEROXIDE (STABILIZED AS NECESSARY)
column168: RECEIVED CALL AT 1950 HOURS OF LEAKING TANK CAR IN 061 TRACK.  UPON ARRIVAL, I FOUND 60# RUPTURE DISC HAD FAILED.  AT APPROXIMATELY 2030, C, SHUPE FROM UNION PACIFIC RAILROAD COMPANY WAS CALLED FOR HELP.  A NEW RUPTURE DISC WAS INSTALLED AND CAR WAS RELEASED.

ON JUNE 4, 1992, B. SAMPLES, M. MCGINNIS, S. SOMMER AND B. HOLLIS MET USAIR FLIGHT 1710.  THE PASSENGER BAGS WERE OFFLOADED FROM THE REAR BIN. B. HOLLIS BEN DROVE A BELT LOADER UP THE FORWARD BIN.  M. MCGINNIS OPENED THE BIN DOOR AND CLIMBED INSIDE.  B. HOLLIS WALKED UP TO THE DOOR INQUIRING IF THERE WERE ANY BAGS.  M. MCGINNIS SAID NO, BUT HER EYES WERE BURNING.  B. HOLLIS TOLD HER TO CLIMB OUT AND HE WOULD GET IN.  AFTER DOING SO, HIS EYES BEGAN TO BURN.  HE CLIMBED OUT AND TOLD THE MAIN RUNNER (S. SOMMER), AND THEN HE WALKED TO THE REAR AND ADVISED B. SAMPLES.  S. SOMMER PULLED HIS TUG UP TO THE BELT LOADER TO GET READY TO ASSIST WITH OFFLOADING THE MAIL B. SAMPLES WAS INFORMED THAT THERE WAS A NASTY SMELL IN THE FRONT BIN.  HE WENT TO THE FRONT BIN, JUMPED IN, AND QUICKLY JUMPED BACK OUT TO THE GROUND WITH HIS EYES WATERING AND GASPING FOR BREATH.  S. SOMMER PICKED UP THE RED SACK OF MAIL, THE BOTTOM OF THE BAG WAS SOAKED WITH SOME SORT OF CHEMICAL.  HE COULD SMELL FUMES ERE IRRITATING TO HIS EYE.  B. SAMPLES REQUESTED THE FIRE DEPT'S HELP IN CHECKING IT OUT.

column62: Loose Closure, Component, or Device; Defective Component or Device
column168: TRAILER 19-5578 WAS DISPATCHED FROM HOUSTON, TX WITH T/O WEAVER/ENROUTE TO JACKSON, MS LAKE CHARLES POLICE OFFICER LEONARD STOPPED DRIVER BECAUSE THEIR WAS A LEAK FROM THE TRAILER.  IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT IT WAS A TOTE TANK FROM A SHIPMENT FROM AQUA PROCESS INC HOUSTON, TX  PRO 384-645671 ON SATURDAY JUNE 6, 1992, CRANE BROS ENVIRONMENTAL WAS CALLED IN TO CLEAN UP THE SPILL.  CHEMTREC WAS CONTACTED AT 0600 AM.  THE INCIDENT HAPPENED AT APPROXIMATELY 0400 AM/6/6/92.  ALL OTHER FREIGHT ON THE TRAILER WAS PULLED OFF AD SORTED WITH SAFETY SUPERVISOR BOBBY SMITH AND ACCOUNT MANAGER/BMT. BROTHERS OF LAKE CHARLES, 1-800-737-8984 WILL DISPOSE OF ALL THE HAZARDOUS MATERIAL AND THE FREIGHT THAT WAS SOILED BY THE LEAK.  TRAILER 19-5578 WAS CLEANED OUT BY THE SAME COMPANY.

column62: Loose Closure, Component, or Device; Inadequate Blocking and Bracing
column168: AT APPROXIMATELY 7:00 AM CHRIS CARLSON BROUGHT TO MY ATTENTION THE CORROSIVE PARCEL AND THE AREA OF SPILLAGE.  I IMMEDIATELY SENT CHRIS TO WASH THE MATERIAL FROM HIS SKIN AND REMOVED THE PARCEL FROM THE WORK AREA. I THEN PROCESSED THE PARCEL ACCORDING TO THE HAZMAT RESPONSE AND DISPOSAL PROCEDURES.  I THEN FOLLOWED UP WITH CHRIS AND WHAT MATERIALS WERE INVOLVED AND TO MAKE SURE HE WAS ALRIGHT.

SHIPMENT WAS DAMAGED AT 0210 ON JUNE 12, 1992.  ONE GLASS INNER RECEPTACLE BROKEN.  BOX MUST HAVE BEEN DROPPED.  SHIPMENT WAS PERFUMERY PRODUCTS WITH FLAMMABLE SOLVENT NOS, UN1266.  SHIPMENT PLACED IN THE DISPOSAL AREA IN A DRUM AWAITING DISPOSITION FROM THE ENVIRONMENTAL AFFAIRS DEPT.  GARRY MORRIS.

THIS WAS NOT A PACKAGING FAILURE.  APPROXIMATELY 22,000 POUNDS OF THIS LIQUID MATERIAL FLOWED OUT OF THE STORAGE TANK (RECEIVING VESSEL) INTO A CONCRETE DIKED AREA.  THERE WAS NO RELEASE TO THE ENVIRONMENT.  THE STORAGE TANK WAS OVERFILLED.  UPON DISCOVERY OF THE OVERFLOWING MATERIAL, THE FLOW OUT OF THE TANK CAR WAS SHUT OFF.  ALL LIQUID WAS PUMPED OUT OF THE DIKED AREA INTO A TANK TRUCK.  THE INTERIOR OF THE DIKE WAS WASHED CLEAN WITH WATER.  THE LAST STEP WAS TO NEUTRALIZE THE DIKE AREA.  ALL WASH WATER AND NEUTRALIZED WATER WERE COLLECTED IN ANOTHER COMPARTMENT OF THE TANK TRUCK.  ARRANGEMENTS ARE BEING MADE FOR THE PROPER DISPOSITION OF THESE MATERIALS.  PROCEDURES ARE NOW IN PLACE TO VERIFY AVAILABLE STORAGE TANK VOLUME BEFORE UNLOADING.  VERBAL REPORT MADE TO NRC NO. 123143.

BAD ODOR IDENTIFIED IN CONTAINER 0670.  HAZMAT RESPONSE TEAM NOTIFIED AND HAD THE CONTAINER REMOVED FROM INDUCTION.  THE RESPONSE TEAM CLEANED UP THE MATERIAL.  CHEMTREC WAS ADVISED.  SHIPMENT BELIEVED TO BE METHYL METHACRYLATE MONOMER, INHIBITED UN 1247.  SHIPMENT WAS NOT OFFERED AS DANGEROUS GOODS.  SHIPMENT WAS HANDED OVER TO THE ENVIRONMENTAL AFFAIRS DEPT FOR INVESTIGATION.  FAA WAS CONTACTED, PICTURES WERE TAKEN BY DAVE KANE/FAA.

column42: GASOLINE INCLUDES GASOLINE MIXED WITH ETHYL ALCOHOL, WITH NOT MORE THAN 10% ALCOHOL
column168: DRIVER JACK KNOWLTON WAS PROCEEDING NORTH ON SOUTHEAST EXPRESSWAY IN BOSTON (SAVIN HILL) WHEN POLICE PULLED HIM OVER.  HIS CARGO TANK HAD A 1"X1/8" GAUGE LEAVING A 1/16TH SQUARE HOLE.  TANK WAS LEAKING A FINE SPRAY. TRUCK WAS TRAVELING FOR ABOUT 15 MINUTES.  IT DID NOT HAVE HOLE WHEN IT LEFT LOADING TERMINAL.  POLICE, FIRE AND COMPANY OFFICIALS SURMISE A PIECE OF SCRAP METAL WAS THROWN UP FROM ROAD CAUSING PUNCTURE.  TANK HAD NO OTHER MARKS ON IT ELIMINATING THE POSSIBILITY OF VEHICLUAR ACCIDENT.

CAR SHOP NOTIFIED ME OF LTC FOUND BY FRA INSPECTOR CONNELLY.  THE INSPECTOR STATED THAT HE FOUND VACUUM RELIEF VALVE INVERTED.  I CONTACTED P&G TO REPAIR T/C.  THEY CONTRACTED SIMPSON & SON WHO REPAIRED CAR BY REPLACING O-RING INSIDE VACUUM RELIEF VALVE.

column62: Improper Preparation for Transportation; Abrasion; Inadequate Blocking and Bracing
column168: AT 1710 HOURS, I WAS NOTIFIED THAT CONTAINER, APLU 116944, WAS LEAKING PRODUCT FROM THE FRONT OF THE CONTAINER.  THE CONTAINER WAS THE UPPER CONTAINER ON DOUBLE STACK FLAT CAR, DTTX 62437.  THE CONTAINER WAS LOADED WITWH TWO TYPES OF HAZARDOUS FREIGHT, (50) 55 GAL DRUMS OF CORROSIVE LIQUID NOS (POLYOXYPROPYLENDIAMINE) AND (8) 55 GAL DRUMS OF POISON LIQUID NOS (CHROMATE).  THE CONTAINER WAS ALSO LOADED WITH 5833 LBS OF NON-HAZARDOUS SYNTHETIC RESIN, WHICH WAS SHRINK WRAPPED ON 5 PALLETS.  THE LADING WAS LOADED IN THREE SECTION.  THE REAR SECTION CONTAINED 26 DRUMS OF THE CORROSIVE MATERIAL, SINGLE DECK.  THE MIDDLE SECTION WAS THE 5 PALLETS OF SYNTHETIC RESIN.  THE FORWARD SECTION WAS SEPARATED FROM THE REST OF THE LOAD WITH PLYWOOD, ROOF TO DECK AND WAS DOUBLE STACKED WITH 24 DRUMS OF CORROSIVE MATERIAL AND 8 PALLETIZED DRUMS OF THE POISON LIQUID NOS.  IN THIS FORWARD SECTION, WE FOUND 2 DRUMS OF THE CORROSIVE LIQUID, NOS THAT SHOWED SIGNS OF LEAKAGE FROM THE BOTTOM CHIME.  THIS APPEARED TO BE CAUSED BY FRICTION AND RUBBING WITH THE PALLETS OF POISONOUS LIQUID NOS.  THESE TWO DRUMS WERE OVERPACKED IN 85 GALLON METAL OVERPACK DRUMS AND RELEASED WITH THE SHIPMENT.  WASTE THAT WAS GENERATED WAS MANIFESTED OUT ON CA. UNIFORM HAZARDOUS WASTE MANIFEST #91601783.  THIS LOAD WAS NOT LOADED NOR BLOCKED & BRACED PROPERLY AS SPECIFIED IN CFR 49, SEC 174.55. A REPRESENTATIVE FROM AMERICAN PRESIDENT LINES WAS ADVISED OF THIS CFR REQUIREMENT AND A REQUEST WAS MADE TO ENSURE THAT FUTURE HAZARDOUS MATERIALS SHIPMENTS BE LOADED AND BLOCKED & BRACED PROPERLY.

column42: PETROLEUM GASES, LIQUEFIED OR LIQUEFIED PETROLEUM GAS
column168: MANAGER HAZARDOUS MATERIAL EMERGENCY RESPONSE, R .M. STINE WAS NOTIFIED BY D.C. HAMPTON, THAT SWITCH CREW HAD REPORTED DUE TO THE FACT THAT MANAGER STINE WAS IN LITTLE ROCK. AR.  SHIPPER'S INSPECTION DETERMINED THAT THE CAR WAS OVERLOADED WITH ZERO OUTAGE.  CAR WAS SPOTTED TO THE EAST FUEL TRACK AND ROGER CASEROLE OF FARMLAND INDUSTRIES HAD TRUCKS RESPOND AND OFF LOAD 3,900 GALLONS OF PRODUCT.

column62: Improper Preparation for Transportation; Inadequate Blocking and Bracing; Too Much Weight on Package
column168: WHILE CONDUCTING ROUTINE INSPECTIONS, SPECIAL AGENT/HAZARDOUS MATERIALS (SA/HM) F.H. LERCH NOTED TRAILER NONZ 24629 HAD THE BOTTOM DOOR PUSHED OUT AND A BLUE MATERIAL HAD LEAKED ON TO THE RIGHT SIDE OF THE TRAILER AND DECK OF FLAT CAR.  SA/HM LERCH'S INSPECTION DETERMINED THE PRODUCT WAS AN ADHESIVE MATERIAL WITH A SOLVENT ODOR.  SA/HM LERCH WAS UNABLE TO CONDUCT AN INTERIOR INSPECTION OF THE TRAILER TO DETERMINE THE SOURCE OF THE LEAK DUE TO THE LOAD SHIFT.  NORTH PLATTE CONTRACT SERVICES WAS CONTACTED TO OFF LOAD TRAILER TO DETERMINE SOURCE OF LEAK.  NORTH PLATTE CONTRACTOR'S RESPONDED AND SOURCE WAS DETERMINED TO BE ONE STEEL PAIL, 5 GALLONS, WAS LAYING ON IT'S SIDE WITH APPROXIMATELY ONE GALLON OF PRODUCT REMAINING IN THE PAIL.  CAUSE APPEARED TO BE INTERNAL PRESSURE RESULTING FROM PAIL BEING PUSHED AGAINST OTHER FREIGHT.  PAIL WAS REPACKAGED AND LOADED ON TRAILER FOR DISPOSAL AT DESTINATION.  TRAILER WAS THEN ADJUSTED, CLOCKED AND BRACED FOR FURTHER MOVEMENT.  JIM MILAZZO OF CHEMTREC AND NEIL HEIL OF NEBRASKA STATE ENVIRONMENTAL WERE NOTIFIED OF THE INCIDENT.
